   <mods:abstract>Jefferson intends to take a ship directly to Norfolk, settle his business
            in Virginia, and then return to Europe by way of New York. Necker's plan was adopted by
            the National Assembly, and may keep payments going until the new government gets into
            motion. During Jefferson's last days in Paris, stocks were so low that he wrote the
            Dutch bankers to ask them to retain the 30,000 gilders until further notice. He
            suggested to Montmorin that cheap salted beef imported from the United States might
            serve to mollify discontent over the scarcity of bread. Although he referred Jefferson's
            proposal to Necker, Montmorin did not favor it, because the French believe that salt
            beef is unhealthy and that it tends to cause scurvy. It might also interfere with the
            gabelle. West Indian ports will continue to be open to American trade for a while. The
            Archbishop of Paris has offered all superfluous church plate, which may be worth five or
            six million pounds sterling, to the treasury.</mods:abstract>
